    <h1>HOWEY OU (OU HONGYI), 18</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201219/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-12-19"><time>2020-12-19</time></a>
        - <span>SPECIAL REPORT</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>Cli­mate ac­tivist, China</p>
    <p>Howey Ou has been called China’s an­swer to Swedish teen cli­mate ac­tivist Greta Thun­berg, who ac­quired fame – and no­to­ri­ety – for skip­ping school on Fri­days to protest out­side Par­lia­ment in Stock­holm.</p>
    <p>Howey stopped go­ing to school when she was 16, af­ter watch­ing An In­con­ve­nient Truth – a doc­u­men­tary on the loom­ing cli­mate catas­tro­phe.</p>
    <p>Since then, she has caught the me­dia’s at­ten­tion with her cam­paign to raise aware­ness of the dan­gers of a warm­ing planet.</p>
    <p>She has held si­lent protests, ini­ti­ated a tree-plant­ing project and taken part in “plog­ging” – pick­ing up lit­ter while jog­ging.</p>
    <p>She tells The Straits Times: “My ac­tions might not lead to con­crete change, but they have po­ten­tial im­pact.</p>
    <p>“To the young peo­ple in China and even around the world, the in­flu­ence shown by a Chi­nese mid­dle school stu­dent is im­pact­ful... and in­spi­ra­tional.”</p>

